Palestinian Autonomous Territories: FMD follow-up report No. 4
--------------------------------------------------------------
Information received on (and dated) 19 Apr 2007 from Dr Imad
Mukarker, Deputy Director General , Veterinary Services and Animal
Health, Ministry of Agriculture, Naplouse, Palestinian Auton. Territories
Summary
Report type: follow-up report No. 4
Start date: 2 Feb 2007
Date of confirmation of event: 8 Feb 2007
Report date: 19 Apr 2007
Date submitted to OIE: 20 Apr 2007
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 20 Jun 2006
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: FMD virus, serotype O
Nature of diagnosis: suspicion, clinical, laboratory (basic),
laboratory (advanced), necropsy
Report pertains to: entire country
New outbreaks
Outbreak 1: Tarameh, Durah, West Bank
Date of start of outbreak: 17 Mar 2007
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not submitted)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals
Species: sheep
Susceptible: 14
Cases: 10
Deaths: 0
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: only young kids less than 30 days old showed
clinical signs. Adult sheep did not show clinical signs, except for
lameness, which lasted 2 days. The post-mortem examination of young
animals revealed typical lesions of "tiger heart". A very high
mortality among lambs and kids aged less than 2 years was observed.
Outbreak 2: Saida, Tulkarem, West Bank
Date of start of outbreak: 17 Mar 2007
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not submitted)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals
Species: sheep
Susceptible: 21
Cases: 2
Deaths: 0
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: only young kids less than 30 days old showed
clinical signs. Adult sheep did not show clinical signs, except for
lameness, which lasted 2 days. The post-mortem examination of young
animals revealed typical lesions of "tiger heart". A very high
mortality among lambs and kids aged less than 2 years was observed.
Outbreak 3: Hezma, Jerusalem, West Bank
Date of start of outbreak: 27 Mar 2007
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not submitted)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals
Species: sheep
Susceptible: 75
Cases: 13
Deaths: 3
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: only young kids less than 30 days old showed
clinical signs. Adult sheep did not show clinical signs, except for
lameness, which lasted 2 days. The post-mortem examination of young
animals revealed typical lesions of "tiger heart". A very high
mortality among lambs and kids aged less than 2 years was observed.
Outbreak 4: Jeftlik, Jericho, West Bank
Date of start of outbreak: 27 Mar 2007
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not submitted)
Epidemiological unit: village
Affected animals
Species: sheep/goat
Susceptible: 550
Cases: 24
Deaths: 10
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: only young kids less than 30 days old showed
clinical signs. Adult sheep did not show clinical signs, except for
lameness, which lasted 2 days. The post-mortem examination of young
animals revealed typical lesions of "tiger heart". A very high
mortality among lambs and kids aged less than 2 years was observed.
Summary of outbreak:
Total outbreaks: 4
Outbreak statistics
Species: sheep
Apparent morbidity rate: 71.43 percent
Apparent mortality rate: 0.00 percent
Apparent case fatality rate: 0.00 percent
Proportion susceptible removed*: 0.00 percent
Species: sheep/goats
Apparent morbidity rate: 6.04 percent
Apparent mortality rate: 2.01 percent
Apparent case fatality rate: 33.33 percent
Proportion susceptible removed*: 2.01 percent
* Removed from the susceptible population either through death,
destruction, or slaughter
Epidemiology
Source of infection:
- introduction of new live animals
- illegal movement of animals
- contact with infected animal(s) at grazing/watering
Epidemiological comments
An intensive mass vaccination was applied in all districts of the
West Bank. The total amount of vaccinated animals is 497 500.
Vaccination is still ongoing. In addition, 16 400 heads of cattle
were vaccinated using O, A, Asia 1 vaccines.
Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: Beit-Dagan laboratory (local laboratory)
Species: sheep/goats
Test: polymerase chain reaction (PCR)
Test date: 29 Mar 2007
Result: positive
Species: sheep/goats
Test: ELISA (enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay)
Test date: 28 Mar 2007
Result: positive
Species: sheep/goats
Test pathogen isolation on cell culture
Test date 03 April 2007
Result Positive
Species: sheep/goats
Test: pathogen isolation on cell culture
Test date: 24 Mar 2007
Result: positive
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[We are grateful for the new information in light of the situation in
Jordan -- see reference below. Of course, it will again be helpful to
know the serotype from both outbreaks in Lebanon as the report
indicates that sheep and goats were vaccinated with type O and did
not get sick in the area of Zahle suburb, Al Biqa, where the dairy
cattle outbreak occurred.
The regular follow-up information from the Palestinian Autonomous
Territories indicating the continued circulation of foot-and-mouth
disease serotype O is also very helpful in putting together a
complete picture of the foot-and-mouth disease situation in the
region, especially as multiple animal health officials are attempting
to control at least 2 serotypes in different types of ruminant
populations. - Mod.PC]
